; Regression test for issue #1793: Unexpected balance report when tracking
; food calories (any commodity equivalence where the "larger" side has a
; quantity != 1).
; https://github.com/ledger/ledger/issues/1793
;
; "C 100 apple = 48 kcal" means 100 apples equal 48 kcal, i.e. 1 apple =
; 0.48 kcal, so 225 apples reduce to 108 kcal.  Before the fix the parser
; dropped the 100 on the left and treated the directive as "1 apple = 48
; kcal", so the reduced balance was 100x too large (10800 kcal instead of
; 108).  The fix normalizes the larger amount to a per-unit rate inside
; amount_t::parse_conversion before setting the smaller/larger links.

commodity apple

C 100 apple = 48 kcal

2019-05-19 Food
    Food:Fruits  225 apple
    Source:Pantry

; With --base the reduce chain is preserved so we see the underlying kcal
; amount.  225 apple * 0.48 kcal/apple = 108 kcal (not 10800).
test bal --base
            108 kcal  Food:Fruits
           -108 kcal  Source:Pantry
--------------------
                   0
end test

; Default balance output preserves the original commodity since 225 apple
; unreduces cleanly.
test bal
           225 apple  Food:Fruits
          -225 apple  Source:Pantry
--------------------
                   0
end test

; -X conversion via the C directive should use the per-unit rate too:
; 225 apple * 0.48 kcal/apple = 108 kcal.
test bal -X kcal
            108 kcal  Food:Fruits
           -108 kcal  Source:Pantry
--------------------
                   0
end test
